Is there a way to make this more formal? Let me try to write it in a more formal mathematical way. 

Assume that there exists a finite set of primes, say P = {p₁, p₂, ..., pₙ}. Let N = (p₁ * p₂ * ... * pₙ) + 1. Then, for each prime p_i in P, N mod p_i = 1, since p_i divides the product, so N = k*p_i + 1, hence remainder 1. Therefore, N is not divisible by any p_i. 

Therefore, N must have a prime factor not in P. But this contradicts the assumption that P contains all primes. Therefore, the assumption is false, so there are infinitely many primes. 

Yes, that seems to be the standard proof. 

